faqSchema:
  - question: "What is IRMAA?"
    answer: "IRMAA (Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amount) is a surcharge added to Medicare Part B and Part D premiums for higher-income beneficiaries. The surcharge is based on your Modified Adjusted Gross Income from two years prior and can add over $1,000/month per person to your Medicare costs."
  - question: "What are the 2025 IRMAA thresholds?"
    answer: "For 2025, single filers with income over $103,000 (married filing jointly over $206,000) will pay IRMAA surcharges. The surcharges increase at multiple income tiers, with the highest tier kicking in at $500,000 for singles and $750,000 for married couples. We help you stay below the first threshold to avoid thousands in extra premiums."
  - question: "Can I avoid IRMAA if I'm already paying it?"
    answer: "Yes, with forward planning. IRMAA is based on income from two years ago, so we manage your income today to avoid surcharges two years from now. We also review potential life-changing event appeals if your income has decreased due to retirement, death of a spouse, or other qualifying events."
  - question: "How does IRMAA affect my Medicare Part D prescription drug coverage?"
    answer: "IRMAA surcharges apply to both Medicare Part B (medical insurance) and Part D (prescription drug coverage). Higher-income beneficiaries pay an additional monthly amount on top of their Part D premium. Strategic income planning can help you avoid these surcharges entirely and significantly reduce your total Medicare costs."
  - question: "When should I start planning for IRMAA?"
    answer: "Ideally, you should start IRMAA planning 3-5 years before Medicare enrollment at age 65. Because IRMAA is based on income from two years prior, early planning allows you to strategically manage Roth conversions, withdrawal sequencing, and other income decisions to minimize future Medicare surcharges. Even if you're already on Medicare, it's never too late to implement strategies that will reduce costs in future years."
